04110nam a22007095i 9780292757349DE-B159720211027022714.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211027t20211997txu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802927573497 a10.7560/7280112doi  a(DE-B1597)587164  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  atxucUS-TX 4aN6538.M4bG37 1998 7aART0150202bisacsh04a704/.0368/720732211 aGaspar de Alba, Alicia, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aChicano Art Inside/Outside the Master’s House :bCultural Politics and the CARA Exhibition /cAlicia Gaspar de Alba. 1aAustin : bUniversity of Texas Press, c[2021] 4c©1997  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tA Theoretical Introduction: Alter-Native Ethnography, a to rasquache -- t1. The Solar of Chicano/a Popular Culture: Mi casa [no] es su casa -- t2. Through Serpent and Eagle Eyes: Intercultural Collaboration -- t3. Out of the House, the Halo, and the Whore s Mask: The Mirror of Malinchismo -- t4. "Between the Ghetto and the Melting Pot": Popular Hegemony -- tConclusion: The Mutation of Multiculturalism -- tAppendix A Selected Viewer Comments -- tAppendix B The Organizational Structure of the CARA Exhibition -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn the early 1990s, a major exhibition Chicano Art: Resistance and Affirmation, 1965-1985 toured major museums around the United States. As a first attempt to define and represent Chicano/a art for a national audience, the exhibit attracted both praise and controversy, while raising fundamental questions about the nature of multiculturalism in the U.S. This book presents the first interdisciplinary cultural study of the CARA exhibit. Alicia Gaspar de Alba looks at the exhibit as a cultural text in which the Chicano/a community affirmed itself not as a "subculture" within the U.S. but as an "alter-Native" culture in opposition to the exclusionary and homogenizing practices of mainstream institutions. She also shows how the exhibit reflected the cultural and sexual politics of the Chicano Movement and how it serves as a model of Chicano/a popular culture more generally. Drawing insights from cultural studies, feminist theory, anthropology, and semiotics, this book constitutes a wide-ranging analysis of Chicano/a art, popular culture, and mainstream cultural politics. It will appeal to a diverse audience in all of these fields.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Okt 2021) 0aMexican American artxPublic opinion. 0aMexican American art-Public opinion. 0aMexican American art. 0aMexican AmericansxCivil rights. 0aMexican Americans-Civil rights. 0aPolitics in art. 7aART / American / General.2bisacsh40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780292757349423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780292757349/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_AD  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_AD  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_ESTMALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA18STMEE  aPDA5EBK